04541nam a22005415i 9780773584150DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735841507 a10.1515/97807735841502doi  a(DE-B1597)657043  a(OCoLC)1394872904  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aML410* 7aBIO0040002bisacsh04a927/.8bL394t2231 aThompson, Brian Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAnthems and Minstrel Shows :bThe Life and Times of Calixa Lavallée, 1842-1891 /cBrian Christopher Thompson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource :b54 photos, 15 drawings, 16 pages of music, 3 maps, 9 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface -- tPrologue: Music and the Nation -- tOn the Road 1842–1873 -- tRebellion 1842–1863 -- tL’Union Nationale: Montreal 1863–1865 -- tThe Journeyman Musician 1866–1873 -- tThe National Musician 1873–1880 -- tParis and Montreal 1873–1878 -- tQuebec City 1878–1880 -- t“The Lafayette of American Music” 1880–1891 -- tBoston 1880–1883 -- tAmerican Concerts and the MTNA 1884–1891 -- tEpilogue -- tCatalogue of Lavallée’s Compositions -- tSelected Compositions -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCalixa Lavallée, the composer of “O Canada,” was the first Canadian-born musician to achieve an international reputation. While primarily remembered for the national anthem, Lavallée and his work extended well beyond Canada, and he played a multitude of roles in North American music as a composer, conductor, administrator, instrumentalist, educator, and critic. In Anthems and Minstrel Shows, Brian Thompson analyzes Lavallée’s music, letters, and published writings, as well as newspapers and music magazines of the time, to provide a detailed account of musical life in nineteenth-century North America and the relationship between music and nation. Leaving Quebec at age sixteen, Lavallée travelled widely for a decade as musical director of a minstrel troupe, and spent a year as a bandsman in the Union Army. Later, as a performer and conductor, he built a repertoire that prepared audiences for the intellectually challenging music of European composers and new music by his US contemporaries. His own music extended from national songs to comic operas, and instrumental music, as he shifted between the worlds of classical and popular music. Previously portrayed as a humble French Canadian forced into exile by ignorance and injustice, Lavallée emerges here as ambitious, radical, bohemian, and fully engaged with the musical, social, and political currents of his time. While nationalism and nation-building are central to this story, Anthems and Minstrel Shows asks to which nation – or nations – Lavallée and “O Canada” really belong.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aComposersxBiographyxCanadaxCanada. 0aComposerszCanadavBiography. 0aComposerszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Composers & Musicians.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358415040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773584150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773584150/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles